A taxonomy is a more elaborate scheme for controlling and categorizing the name of things. Taxonomies are frequently hierarchical in nature, defining not only the terms for individual things but the names for the classes of things. Thus a taxonomy does not just list sparrows and blue jays and robins, it also classifies them as birds, and birds as animals, and animals as living things. A good taxonomy should be specific to the domain for which it is intended. (Blue Jays and Cardinals occupy a very different place in a baseball taxonomy than in a ornithological taxonomy.

This reference to Blue Jays and Cardinals is a culturally dependent one. Readers outside North America may not recognize these as the names of baseball teams. This is very much a concern for terminology management and could call for differences in rhetoric in different markets (such as a footnote to explain the reference to those who might not be familiar with it, or perhaps a totally different example being substituted to better explain to concept to another culture).
) As a classification scheme, a taxonomy may be used not only as the basis for controlling vocabulary, but also as a basis for top-down navigation of a content set.
